{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b86dd4bb-41b1-4e4b-8dbb-8d42ed78e3a3","content":"In .NET MAUI, those methods moved from `Application` to the **`Window`** class. Create a custom `Window` subclass and override the lifecycle methods:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()      // was OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnStopped()      // was OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnStopped();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()      // was OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen wire it up in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\npublic class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        return new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Quick mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |\n\nAdditional window events like `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, and `OnDestroying()` are also available for finer-grained control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5ea7bb9c-20f4-4d16-b522-c3290153a1cf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI, specifically about the Application lifecycle methods (OnStart, OnSleep, OnResume). This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the approach changed. You use the lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can use the `Window` lifecycle events. Actually, let me be more precise:\n\n\n- `OnStart` doesn't have a direct equivalent on the Application class, but you can hook into `CreateWindow` or the `Window.Created` event\n- `OnSleep` and `OnResume` are handled through platform-specific lifecycle events configured via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`, like `OnPause` for Android or `DidEnterBackground` for iOS\n\nWait, I should double-check this — the `Application` class in .NET MAUI might still have these methods, just not as the recommended approach anymore.\n\nActually, I need to be clearer here. The `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Application` class doesn't expose `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` as virtual methods the way Xamarin.Forms did. Instead, MAUI shifted to using `Window` lifecycle methods like `OnCreated`, `OnActivated`, `OnDeactivated`, `OnStopped`, and `OnResumed`, plus platform-specific lifecycle event configuration in `MauiProgram.cs`. For migrating from Xamarin.Forms, `OnStart` would map to something like overriding the window creation or using the lifecycle events. So the complete mapping is `OnStart` to `OnCreated()`, `OnSleep` to either `OnStopped()` or `OnDeactivated()`, and `OnResume` to `OnResumed()` or `OnActivated()`. I'll provide some code examples to make this clearer.","outputTokens":1088,"requestId":"102E:2A621F:14C9335:176A980:69FD34FF"},"id":"4d3ce570-1df7-479e-aa7d-6df18bdada65","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:57:55.907Z","parentId":"50fa70c8-fbf3-4c5d-ad62-2b5b92f125ce"}
